{"query": "What actions can be taken in urban environments to create or protect foraging and roosting habitat for bats?", "summary": "Several actions can be taken in urban environments to create or protect foraging and roosting habitat for bats. For foraging habitat, creating or restoring bat foraging habitat in urban areas has shown positive results, with studies finding greater bat activity over biodiverse green roofs than conventional unvegetated roofs, and greater bat activity for three of five bat species over green roofs than over conventional roofs (action 954). Protecting brownfield or ex-industrial sites can also provide foraging habitat, with one study finding five bat species recorded within a protected urban wildlife refuge on an abandoned manufacturing site (action 953).

For roosting habitat, providing bat boxes is widely documented as effective, with 41 of 43 studies finding that bats used bat boxes installed in various habitats including urban areas and buildings (action 1024). Studies found that the number of bats using bat boxes increased by 2-10 times up to 10 years after installation, and that 72 bat species have been found to use bat boxes, with 18 species commonly using them (action 1024). Creating alternative bat roosts within developments shows mixed success, with studies finding that bat boxes or bat lofts were used by bats at 13-74% of development sites (action 949).

Creating artificial hollows and cracks in trees can provide roosting sites, with one study finding that eight of 16 artificial hollows cut into trees were used by roosting long-eared bats (action 2047). Creating artificial caves or hibernacula is another option, with studies finding that artificial hibernacula were used by up to four bat species, and the number of bats using an artificial hibernaculum increased in each of nine years after construction (action 2049). Managing the microclimate of artificial bat roosts can improve their effectiveness, with one study finding more bats in artificial roosts after they were modified to reduce internal temperatures (action 2052).", "action_ids": ["954","953","1024","949","2047","2049","2052"]}

